webtransportd — change log
==========================

Unreleased
----------

Module foundations (cycles 1–20)
--------------------------------

* Cycles 1–11 — length-prefixed frame codec: flag byte + 1/2/4-byte
  QUIC-style varint + payload. Every error path (reserved bits,
  BUF_TOO_SMALL, INCOMPLETE, MAX_PAYLOAD cap) fenced under ASAN.
* Cycle 12 — log module: level filter, thread-safe mutex-guarded
  stderr emit.
* Cycles 13–15 — env module: WEBTRANSPORT_* CGI set and --passenv
  whitelist.
* Cycle 16 — child_process: fork + execvp with three pipes, SIGTERM
  + reap under timeout.
* Cycles 17–18 — peer_session: mutex-guarded FIFO work queue and
  reader thread that decodes child stdout into frames on the queue.
* Cycles 19–20 — webtransportd binary entry: argv parsing and
  --version, smoke-tested via fork/exec.

Vendored build bring-up (cycles 21a–c)
--------------------------------------

* 21a — error_names.c from picoquic compiles and links under the
  Godot-style preprocessor set; vendored TUs use -w so their
  warnings don't fight our -Werror.
* 21b — every thirdparty/picoquic/picoquic/*.c (50 TUs) compiles.
* 21c — the full vendored stack (picoquic + picohttp + picotls +
  mbedtls + cifra + micro-ecc + loglib; 217 TUs) compiles and
  links. picoquic_create(...) returns non-NULL under ASAN+UBSAN.

Daemon wiring (cycles 21d.1–22e)
--------------------------------

* 21d.1 — webtransportd --selftest exercises the full mbedtls TLS
  init path inside the daemon binary. Documents the darwin-arm64
  ASAN/pthread_create quirk (pc=0 in the thread entry) that pushes
  us toward a synchronous packet loop on the main thread.
* 21d.2 — in-process client+server handshake reaches
  picoquic_state_ready via synchronous packet pumping. No sockets,
  no pthread.
* 21d.3 — real-socket handshake over loopback UDP.
* 22a — --exec=<bin> spawns the configured child on first cnx-ready,
  reaps on shutdown.
* 22b — peer_session reader thread attaches to spawned child's
  stdout_fd; decoded frames surface on the daemon log.
* 22c — server_stream_cb frames inbound QUIC stream bytes into the
  child's stdin_fd.
* 22d — decoded outbound frames echo back via picoquic_add_to_stream
  so the client sees its own bytes. v0.1 echo works end-to-end.
* 22e — datagram symmetry: flag=1 frames round-trip via
  picoquic_queue_datagram_frame on both sides.

Hardening and polish (cycles 23–30)
-----------------------------------

* 23 — dedicated pthread forwards child stderr_fd to the daemon's
  own stderr, prefixed "child stderr: ".
* 24 — deterministic fuzz harness for the frame codec
  (frame_fuzz_test). Catches OOB reads on any malformed prefix
  under ASAN.
* 25 — decoder accepts the QUIC 8-byte varint form (prefix 0b11)
  that previously silently fell into the 4-byte branch.
* 26 — SIGTERM/SIGINT is the only shutdown path; removed the 1 s
  auto-exit-after-ready timer.
* 27 — --log-level=<0..4> wires log.c into the daemon.
* 28 — log lines now carry a [LEVEL] prefix; every fprintf(stderr)
  in the daemon routed through wtd_log (forwarder thread included).
* 29 — per-cnx wtd_peer_t list. Each cnx gets its own spawned
  child, peer_session reader, and echo target. Two concurrent
  clients no longer trample each other's state.
* 30 — richer --help output: description, per-subcommand
  breakdown, options table, framing spec note.

Ship prep (cycles 31–34)
------------------------

* 31 — LICENSE (BSD-2-Clause) for first-party code; vendored
  libraries keep their upstream terms.
* 32 — examples/echo.c, a minimal C reference child.
  handshake_echo_test switched from /bin/cat to this helper so the
  round trip exercises our codec on the child side too.
* 33 — daemon-launching tests derive their UDP port from the test
  pid to avoid the retry-flake when a previous run's daemon hasn't
  fully released the port.
* 34 — examples/frame-helper.sh for shell-level framing. One
  (flag, payload) -> framed envelope on stdout, python3 handles
  the varint widths.

Portability and CI (cycles 35–39)
---------------------------------

* 35 — AUTHORS and CHANGES files land as first-party docs.
* 36 — GitHub Actions CI matrix: linux-gcc (ubuntu-latest),
  macos-clang (macos-latest), windows-mingw (MSYS2 + mingw-w64).
  POSIX jobs run `make test` under ASAN+UBSAN; the Windows job
  overrides CFLAGS/LDFLAGS to disable sanitizers (mingw's ASAN is
  unreliable). All three smoke --version and upload the binary.
* 37 — Win32 branch in child_process.c: CreatePipe ×3 with
  SetHandleInformation on the parent-side ends, CreateProcessA
  with STARTF_USESTDHANDLES, and _open_osfhandle to wrap pipe
  HANDLEs as CRT file descriptors so the daemon's existing
  read/write/close calls work unchanged. WTD_CHILD_PID_NONE hides
  the pid_t vs HANDLE switch from callers.
* 38 — Makefile ordering fix. The webtransportd: target listed
  $(VENDOR_ALL_OBJS) as a prerequisite but the variable was
  defined ~130 lines later; GNU make expands prerequisite lists
  at parse time, so the expansion silently yielded the empty
  string and no vendored .o files were scheduled to build. Local
  macOS worked because prior builds left .o files in the tree;
  CI starts clean and link bombed across all three jobs. Moved
  the vendor blocks above the rule.
* 39 — Linux and Windows platform fixes exposed once cycle 38
  unblocked the CI build. Added -D_GNU_SOURCE -D_DARWIN_C_SOURCE
  to CFLAGS so glibc exposes strdup/setenv/unsetenv/environ under
  -std=c11 (macOS headers hid the bug locally). Wrapped the
  POSIX-only helpers in child_process_test.c in #ifndef _WIN32
  so pid-as-HANDLE doesn't break the compile under mingw.
* Win32 `child_process.c` (cycle 37) — `CreatePipe` ×3 with
  `SetHandleInformation` on the parent-side ends, `CreateProcessA`
  with `STARTF_USESTDHANDLES`, `_open_osfhandle` wraps the pipe
  handles so the daemon's existing read/write/close calls still
  work. `WTD_CHILD_PID_NONE` hides the pid_t vs HANDLE switch from
  callers.
* Deterministic daemon-launch ports in tests (cycle 33) —
  the three tests that fork/exec `./webtransportd` now derive their
  port from the test process's pid: `20000 + (getpid() & 0x1fff)`.
  A stale daemon from a previous failed run lands on a different
  port once its pid is reused; odds of two concurrent test runs
  colliding are ~1/8000. Could still be tightened by adding
  `--port=0` + printing the bound port from the daemon.
